MissionCommands.Message: {{profileName}}, we are getting closer to Earth and your last phase of the journey!
We will start by performing a short mid-course correction (MCC) to move Pe so we reach an entry angle of 6.5 degrees.
Once we are on a proper trajectory, we will start preparing for atmospheric entry, and landing.
Lets verify our trajectory and perform a mid-course correction.
Roger. You are on an entry trajectory, so open the CSM Burn Tool and set both phase and dV to 0 to see your flight path angle at entry interface. Press READY when done.
Ready.
A dV of about 5 fps in prograde direction is needed to correct the trajectory as we are so close to Earth. We will use a manual approach for the burn, just to test the EMS.
Roger.
Manually maneuver the craft to a PROGRADE attitude, DIRECT RCS should be enabled. Press READY when ready.
Then set the EMS to Standby.
Then the EMS Mode to dV SET.
Then set the dV to +5 fps.
Then set the EMS to Normal.
Then the EMS mode selector to dV.

Great. Use the translation RCS to burn prograde (foward) until the EMS reaches 0. You can check the achieved entry angle again using the burn tool (reset the tool first), but it does not need to be perfect. Press PROCEED when ready.
Roger. Mid-course correction complete.
Reset the EMS and then use timescale to reach MET 140 hours and 40 minutes. Press PROCEED when you have done so.
Let's start the preparations for entry. We will guide you through the steps as in the academy.

First set up the EMS. Set V0 to the 36500 as we are performing a Lunar trajectory entry. To do this, press INC on the dV/EMS SET thumb switch a few times so the script line is aligned with the display line.
Set the ENTRY EMS 0.05g switch to UP to ARM the EMS.
Then set the EMS mode to ENTRY and keep it in STBY.
The initial program to prepare for entry is P61, the Entry Preparation program.
On the CMC, run V37E 61E to start the entry preparations.
The first input will be the predicted latitude and longitude of the splashdown location, and the last is if the initial entry will be heads up (+1) or heads down (-1). This controls the lift vector.
The capsule has been designed to have an aerodynamic lift vector, and is opposite of the direction of the heads. So if the heads are pointing down, the vector points up etc.
This vector is used to maneuver the capsule during entry, just like an aeroplane.
Press PRO to accept the default values.
Next, V06N60 shows predictions for entry, like the predicted g-force, velocity at entry interface and flight path angle between the intertial velocity and the local horizontal at the entry interface.
The entry interface is at around 400k of altitude.
Press PRO to accept the values. The next screen shows more predictions like range to go from 0.05g, the predicted velocity at 0.05g and time until 0.05g.
Press PRO to accept. P61 now automatically moves to P62 - the CM/SM Separation and Preentry Maneuver.
P62 first displays V50N25, with 41 in R1. This means Please Perform: Checklist item: 41. This is CM/SM separation.
Check the SPS DEORBIT & ENTRY CHECKLIST, section 30.
The CM RCS system needs to be enabled, as the SM RCS system will be jettisoned soon. Verify that the CM RCS LOGIC is set to ON.
Set the CM RCS Propellant 1 system on MDC-2 to ARM (UP).
Do the same for the CM RCS Propellant 2 system. The CM RCS system will now automatically be ready when the SM is jettisoned.
Set the SC CONT to SCS.
Ok guys, time to separate the SM. It sure has been a good companion during this journey.
Set the CM/SM Sep switch 1 to UP.
Set the CM/SM Sep switch 2 to UP.
Ok, Separation. There she goes, drifting away.
Set the SC CONT switch to CMC again.
Press PRO on the computer.
This activates the entry DAP and once again displays predicted landing point and gives you an opportunity to select the initial lift vector.
Press PRO to accept the data. The CM will now move into the entry attitude, and when within limits, the CMC will automatically proceed to P63.
P63 initially displays V06 N64, showing the current drag acceleration, velocity and range to splash. Key V16E to monitor this.
The program will mainly keep you updated with the drag acceleration, and will automatically move to P64 at 0.05g. The DAP will maintain a stable attitude.
As we are travelling at a velocity of about 36000 ft/s, we will need to bleed off the excess velocity that will take us back to the Moon. As we hit the atmosphere heads down, we will dive into it.

This will start the deceleration, and the first target is to reduce the velocity down to 25.500 ft/s. As we do this pay attention to the instruments. The G-forces will start to build up, so try and maintain a maximum G-force of about 7 G's.
To miantain this, use the EMS and roll to generate lift in the correct direction, either dive down into the increasing density (more drag and G's) or up to reduce the G-acceleration.
Feel free to use timescale, but be careful as we need time for the final preparations. Resume normal count at the Entry Interphase mark. P64 will start once 0.05g is detected.
Set EMS mode to NORMAL. We will perform a manual entry. This means we only need to control roll as the other axes are controlled by aerodynamic forces.
Set CMC to FREE and verify the RHC is powered.
P64 will decide the next step based on many factors, such as vertical speed. For Earth Entry, it will move to P67.
When in P67, the roll is used to guide the capsules lift vector and towards the splashdown point. This is when the high G forces take place. The EMS will draw a line showing the G force and velocity.
Set the SC CONT to SCS as soon when the entry guidance is complete (P67 displays V16 N67). Check Landing checklist on the Mission Pad.
Insert the two ELS fuses on the left hand MDC-8 panel (the lowest row of fuses). Close ELS Bat A first.
Then close the ELS BAT B.
Then ARM the ELS LOGIC on MDC-1, it's a protected switch.
Follow the landing checklist to set up the cockpit for landing.
The ELS should deploy the chuts, starting with the drogue, then the main and then splashdown. This system is automatic, but be ready for manually control using the push buttons on MDC-1.
Drogue chute is deployed!
Main chute is out!
Excellent work, is has been a long journey, but it's great to be back home after this.
Welcome home, {{capsuleName}}!
It sure has, an epic journey to the Moon and back.
And who knows, we might return.
And splash!

Title: HEAT
Description: The Atmospheric entry is the final remaining task, and is one of the more complex procedures. With an narrow entry corridor, the crew must be on a strickt trajectory to hit the atmosphere correctly, and maneuver through it to avoid excessive G-forces or heat. Once throgh, the chutes and the landing system must safely bring the craft and the crew to a splash in the ocean.
BriefingText:
The goal of the final phase of the mission is to perform an atmospheric entry and land the spacecraft.

Atmoshperic Entry:
You will perform a simplified mid-course correction (MCC) to bring the spacecraft on a trajectory that targets an angle of 6.5 at the entry interface (EI). EI takes place at an altitude of 400k ft.
After EI, the craft will soon start to decelerate and will go heads down into the atmosphere. Once the craft starts building altitude, the CM should be rolled to heads up, so it dives back into the atmosphere. Once altitude is reducing again, the CM is rolled back to heads down, to limit the G-loads. Roll can then be used to maintain a G-load of maximum 9 as velocity transforms to heat.

Landing
The Earth Landing System (ELS) is used to bring the spacecraft down after entry. Drogues will decelerate the craft further before the mains performs the final bit.
